<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="575" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,690,1363]" pageId="6" pageNumber="575">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1266,1291]" pageId="6" pageNumber="575">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. The new species has typical body form for 
<taxonomicName box="[828,949,1267,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hephathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="575" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[828,949,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="575">Hephathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the relatively wide aedeagus, the apical gonopore, and the apically blunt style.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,993,1338,1363]" pageId="6" pageNumber="575" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,690,1363]" box="[199,993,1338,1363]" pageId="6" pageNumber="575">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1338,1363]" pageId="6" pageNumber="575">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet refers to the relatively wide aedeagus.
</paragraph>
